www.mimecast.com


Mimecast is an international company specializing in cloud-based email management for Microsoft Exchange and Microsoft Office 365,[1] including security, archiving, and continuity services to protect business mail.



Contents


1 History
2 Founding
3 Technology
4 Awards
5 References



History[edit]
Mimecast was founded in 2003 by Peter Bauer and Neil Murray. It has offices in London, Boston, Chicago, San Francisco, Dallas, Cape Town, Johannesburg and Melbourne.[2]
In January, 2010, the company raised $21 million in Series B financing[3] from Index Ventures and Dawn Capital.
By June 2015 Mimecast had 14,500 customers,[4] up from 7,000 in 2007.
In September 2012 Mimecast raised $62m in a Series C funding round, led by New York-based Insight Venture Partners.[5]
Founding[edit]
Mimecast co-founder and CEO, Peter Bauer, previously founded FAB Technology in the mid-nineties and sold it to Idion. Earlier, Peter trained as a Microsoft systems engineer and worked with corporate messaging systems.[6]
Mimecast co-founder and CTO is Neil Murray, previously CTO at Global Technology Services and founder of Pro-Solutions,[7] he leads the development of all the company's technology, overseeing the architecture of Mimecast's service and sets out the overall technical vision and strategy for the service.[8]
Other executives include Mimecast Chief Scientist Nathaniel Borenstein, who was amongst the original designers of the MIME protocol for formatting multimedia Internet electronic mail - he sent the world's first e-mail attachment on 11 March 1992.[9]
Technology[edit]
The service uses a massively-parallel grid infrastructure for email storage and processing[10] through geographically dispersed data centers,[11] enabling it to offer a 100% uptime service level agreement on all services.[12] Its Mail Transfer Agent provides intelligent email routing based on server or user mailbox location.[13]
Email Security

Secure Email Gateway: user optimized spam protection,[14] malware, DoS and DHA protection. Real-time diagnostic and reporting; data loss prevention, secure message delivery, email branding and disclaimer management, document conversion and metadata management, real-time online queue management, large attachment management, advanced routing and spooling.[15]
Targeted Threat Protection: URL rewriting at the gateway with time-of-click scanning for malicious content before being opened.[16]
Large File Send: send and receive large files from Outlook, with encryption, optional access key and custom expiration dates.[17]
Secure Messaging: secure email channel for sensitive information either user-initiated or policy-driven.[18]

Enterprise Information Archiving

Cloud Archive for Email: Encrypted cloud storage which saves emails in triplicate[19] in an immutable storage system.[20] Users can access and search emails through an Outlook desktop client.[21] Archive access is available via a Mac desktop app and apps for Android, BlackBerry, iOS[22] and Windows Mobile devices.

Mailbox Continuity

Continuity: During primary mail system outages, email can be accessed via Microsoft Outlook, through a web browser[23] and via mobile devices.[24]

Awards[edit]

Best Cloud Specialist Vendor of the Year 2014 - CRN Channel Awards.[25]
2013 Healthcare IT Summit XCellence Awards.[26]
2013 Deloitte Technology Fast 50.[27]
One of London Stock Exchange's '1000 companies to inspire Britain' 2013.[28]
Computing Security Awards 2012: Messaging Security Solution of the Year.[29]
Microsoft Worldwide Partner Conference: Innovative Customer Advocacy Partner of the Year.[30]
Sunday Times Tech Track 100 2012: Ranked 45th.[31]
UK Deloitte Technology Fast 50 2012: Ranked 20th.[32]
Computer Reseller News Channel Awards 2012: Security Vendor of the Year.[33]

